  "elements": [
    {
      "id": "v2wG8_RkERMP7t9qyKXVi",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -192.93749786773947,
      "y": -1556.504917976859,
      "width": 1586.5999755859375,
      "height": 2800,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0J",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 91791453,
      "version": 8918,
      "versionNonce": 343245521,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1766694141628,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Functional Requirements - \n1. User should be able to upload a video\n2. User should be able to download a video\n3. User should be able to share the video to others\n3. Users should be able to see the video shared by others.\n4. Users should be able to sync the video across their devices.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements\n1. User should be leverage resumable-upload and resumable-download.\n2. Users should get a response irrespective of the data being stale or updated (high availability)\n3. Users should be able to upload a content of max 50 GB.\n4. No data should be lost.\n5. The system should be scalable to support Billions of contents\n6. The latency should be low.\n\n\nAPI Contracts - \n\n1. UPLOAD A VIDEO  \nPOST /upload --> Pre-signedURL and status\n        body {\n                  title:<>\n                  description:<>\n                  timestamp:<>\n                  size:<>\n                  chunkList:<>\n               }\n\n2. DOWNLOAD A VIDEO\nGET /download/<videoId> --> VideoMetadata & status\n\n3. SHARE FILES WITH OTHERS\nPOST /addUser/<VideoId>\n        body {userID: , timestamp:<>} --> ConfirmationId and status\n\n4. VIEW CONTENTS\nGET /User/<UserId> --> List of Videos<Id, title, description, timestamp, size> and status\n\n5. SYNC VIDEO\nGET /Sync?lastSyncedTimestamp={} -->  List of videos & status\n\n\nData Flow -\n\n1. Device1 wants to upload a video (Functional Requirement #1 and non-functional requirement #3 satisfied)\n    a. Device1 will make a request to the Dropbox Service to upload a video with the details in the API contract.\n    b. The Dropbox Service will make a request to S3 to get a pre-signed URL.\n    c. The Dropbox Service will then return pre-signed URL to the Device1 and persist the information in the contentMetadata.\n    d. The service will add ContentId and userId to the ContentAccess table.\n    e. Device 1 can upload the video to S3 directly [More to come...]\n\n2. User1 wants to share the video with User2 (Functional Requirement #3 satisfied)\n    a. User1 makes a POST request to Dropbox Service which adds another row of <ContentId>:<userId>\n    b. The service returns a confirmation status to the User1.\n\n3. User2 wants to download a video (Functional Requirement #2 satisfied)\n    a. User1 requested Dropbox Service to provide a shareable link (which can be the id)\n    b. User1 shared the shareableLink to User 2 which makes a GET call to dropbox service to download the video.\n    c. The service will first check the access via ContentAccessTable and retrieve the metadata from content DB for USer2's device to render.\n    d. When User2 click on the video thumbnail rendered on the device, the device will download the content from Content Delivery Network (geography-based)\n    e. If the CDN does not have the content, it will fetch from S3 else you\n\n4. User should be able to view their contents (Functional Requirement #4 satisfied)\n    a. The service will retrieve the list of videos that user1 has access to via the ContentAccessTable.\n    b. Then it will retrieve the information required to render the videos from the ContentMetadata table and return the List of videos.\n\n\n5. User wants to sync all the contents to their devices. Device 1 uploaded the video but Device2 hasn't received the video (Functional Requirement #5 satisfied)\n   a. Device1 and Device2 can do periodic polling using Server Sent Event Communication. (Open a channel, receive multiple messages from server and close it)\n   b. When Device2 open a communication with the service, it will send a GET Sync request with the LastSyncedTimestamp\n   c. At this moment, the dropbox service will retrieve the list of videos whose lastModifiedTimestamp > LastSyncedTimestamp from ContentMetadataDB\n   d. Then, it will check the ContentAccessTable to see if the UserID has permissions.\n   e. If all the conditions are met, it will send the required metadata to render on the device2.\n   f. Device2 on clicking the video thumbnail, it will download the video to the local DB via S3 link.\n\n\n 6. User should be able to perform resumable-upload. (Non-functional requirement #1 and #4 is satisfied)\n    a. When a User1 decides to upload a video, it will needs to break the video into chunks of 5-10MB [using split command in Linux]\n    b. Post that, it should persist the information in its own local DB.\n    c. As per #1, it will make a POST request to the Service to upload the video. So, now the API contract will include chunkList in the body.\n    d. For every chunk, dropbox will return a S3 Link.\n    e. Now user1 will upload the chunk in its respective S3 Link.\n    f. So, incase of network outage, Devices can query the Dropbox service to return the list of chunks whose upload status is NotStarted or InProgress.\n    g. Post that, devices can resume uploading the remaining of the chunks.\n    h. On completion of the chunk upload, the devices should ping the dropbox service to update the uploadStatus.\n    i. Post that, the device should update the UploadStatus of the ContentMetadata table.\n    i. Optional: The service should validate with S3 if the file is present. [Not to be dependent on user's actions]\n\n7. Similarly, User2 wants to perform resumable-downlod (Non-functional requirement #1 and #4 is satisfied)\n    a. As soon as the USer2 clicks on the thumbnail image, dropbox service returns list of chunks\n    b. User2 can maintain the download status of those chunks in its local DB.\n    c. So, incase of network outage, Devices can depend on its local DB to continue the installation of NotStarted or InProgress chunks using the S3 Link.\n    d. Post that, the device should update the downloadStatus of ContentMetadataTable.\n\nNOTE: Sync will not change with resumable-upload and resumable-download. The purpose of sync is to just to show the new content\n         with thumbnail, title, description, size, etc. Once the user clicks on the thumbnail, download will start (As per #7)\n\n\nLet's talk about scalability - (Non-functional requirement #5 is satisfied)\n   1. We can horizontally scale The Dropbox Service.\n   2. We can shard/parition/replicas of ContentDB based on UserID.\n\nLet's talk about availability - (Non-functional requirement #2 is satisfied)\n   1. If a user uploads a new version of the content and if another legitimate user request a download, \n      then if the new upload is not completed, we will let the other user download the previous version of the content based on the upload status and ContentID\n\n    \n High Level Design \n\n\n \n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Functional Requirements - \n1. User should be able to upload a video\n2. User should be able to download a video\n3. User should be able to share the video to others\n3. Users should be able to see the video shared by others.\n4. Users should be able to sync the video across their devices.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements\n1. User should be leverage resumable-upload and resumable-download.\n2. Users should get a response irrespective of the data being stale or updated (high availability)\n3. Users should be able to upload a content of max 50 GB.\n4. No data should be lost.\n5. The system should be scalable to support Billions of contents\n6. The latency should be low.\n\n\nAPI Contracts - \n\n1. UPLOAD A VIDEO  \nPOST /upload --> Pre-signedURL and status\n        body {\n                  title:<>\n                  description:<>\n                  timestamp:<>\n                  size:<>\n                  chunkList:<>\n               }\n\n2. DOWNLOAD A VIDEO\nGET /download/<videoId> --> VideoMetadata & status\n\n3. SHARE FILES WITH OTHERS\nPOST /addUser/<VideoId>\n        body {userID: , timestamp:<>} --> ConfirmationId and status\n\n4. VIEW CONTENTS\nGET /User/<UserId> --> List of Videos<Id, title, description, timestamp, size> and status\n\n5. SYNC VIDEO\nGET /Sync?lastSyncedTimestamp={} -->  List of videos & status\n\n\nData Flow -\n\n1. Device1 wants to upload a video (Functional Requirement #1 and non-functional requirement #3 satisfied)\n    a. Device1 will make a request to the Dropbox Service to upload a video with the details in the API contract.\n    b. The Dropbox Service will make a request to S3 to get a pre-signed URL.\n    c. The Dropbox Service will then return pre-signed URL to the Device1 and persist the information in the contentMetadata.\n    d. The service will add ContentId and userId to the ContentAccess table.\n    e. Device 1 can upload the video to S3 directly [More to come...]\n\n2. User1 wants to share the video with User2 (Functional Requirement #3 satisfied)\n    a. User1 makes a POST request to Dropbox Service which adds another row of <ContentId>:<userId>\n    b. The service returns a confirmation status to the User1.\n\n3. User2 wants to download a video (Functional Requirement #2 satisfied)\n    a. User1 requested Dropbox Service to provide a shareable link (which can be the id)\n    b. User1 shared the shareableLink to User 2 which makes a GET call to dropbox service to download the video.\n    c. The service will first check the access via ContentAccessTable and retrieve the metadata from content DB for USer2's device to render.\n    d. When User2 click on the video thumbnail rendered on the device, the device will download the content from Content Delivery Network (geography-based)\n    e. If the CDN does not have the content, it will fetch from S3 else you\n\n4. User should be able to view their contents (Functional Requirement #4 satisfied)\n    a. The service will retrieve the list of videos that user1 has access to via the ContentAccessTable.\n    b. Then it will retrieve the information required to render the videos from the ContentMetadata table and return the List of videos.\n\n\n5. User wants to sync all the contents to their devices. Device 1 uploaded the video but Device2 hasn't received the video (Functional Requirement #5 satisfied)\n   a. Device1 and Device2 can do periodic polling using Server Sent Event Communication. (Open a channel, receive multiple messages from server and close it)\n   b. When Device2 open a communication with the service, it will send a GET Sync request with the LastSyncedTimestamp\n   c. At this moment, the dropbox service will retrieve the list of videos whose lastModifiedTimestamp > LastSyncedTimestamp from ContentMetadataDB\n   d. Then, it will check the ContentAccessTable to see if the UserID has permissions.\n   e. If all the conditions are met, it will send the required metadata to render on the device2.\n   f. Device2 on clicking the video thumbnail, it will download the video to the local DB via S3 link.\n\n\n 6. User should be able to perform resumable-upload. (Non-functional requirement #1 and #4 is satisfied)\n    a. When a User1 decides to upload a video, it will needs to break the video into chunks of 5-10MB [using split command in Linux]\n    b. Post that, it should persist the information in its own local DB.\n    c. As per #1, it will make a POST request to the Service to upload the video. So, now the API contract will include chunkList in the body.\n    d. For every chunk, dropbox will return a S3 Link.\n    e. Now user1 will upload the chunk in its respective S3 Link.\n    f. So, incase of network outage, Devices can query the Dropbox service to return the list of chunks whose upload status is NotStarted or InProgress.\n    g. Post that, devices can resume uploading the remaining of the chunks.\n    h. On completion of the chunk upload, the devices should ping the dropbox service to update the uploadStatus.\n    i. Post that, the device should update the UploadStatus of the ContentMetadata table.\n    i. Optional: The service should validate with S3 if the file is present. [Not to be dependent on user's actions]\n\n7. Similarly, User2 wants to perform resumable-downlod (Non-functional requirement #1 and #4 is satisfied)\n    a. As soon as the USer2 clicks on the thumbnail image, dropbox service returns list of chunks\n    b. User2 can maintain the download status of those chunks in its local DB.\n    c. So, incase of network outage, Devices can depend on its local DB to continue the installation of NotStarted or InProgress chunks using the S3 Link.\n    d. Post that, the device should update the downloadStatus of ContentMetadataTable.\n\nNOTE: Sync will not change with resumable-upload and resumable-download. The purpose of sync is to just to show the new content\n         with thumbnail, title, description, size, etc. Once the user clicks on the thumbnail, download will start (As per #7)\n\n\nLet's talk about scalability - (Non-functional requirement #5 is satisfied)\n   1. We can horizontally scale The Dropbox Service.\n   2. We can shard/parition/replicas of ContentDB based on UserID.\n\nLet's talk about availability - (Non-functional requirement #2 is satisfied)\n   1. If a user uploads a new version of the content and if another legitimate user request a download, \n      then if the new upload is not completed, we will let the other user download the previous version of the content based on the upload status and ContentID\n\n    \n High Level Design \n\n\n \n",
